WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.360 --> 00:00:06.660
MATTHEW: Our guest today
is Gavin Newsom.

00:00:06.660 --> 00:00:08.780
He is the Lieutenant Governor
of State of California and

00:00:08.780 --> 00:00:12.120
also the Former Mayor of San
Francisco for seven years.

00:00:12.120 --> 00:00:14.550
He's always been a longtime
champion of

00:00:14.550 --> 00:00:16.140
innovation and civics.

00:00:16.140 --> 00:00:19.460
And also in, I think, social
development, especially

00:00:19.460 --> 00:00:22.800
famously being, when he was
mayor, advocating for same sex

00:00:22.800 --> 00:00:24.570
marriage for a while, even
though it's against the law.

00:00:24.570 --> 00:00:25.450
Which is why--

00:00:25.450 --> 00:00:26.920
GAVIN NEWSOM: You don't have
to remind people of that.

00:00:26.920 --> 00:00:28.060
MATTHEW: [INAUDIBLE].

00:00:28.060 --> 00:00:32.009
What you may not know about
Gavin is that he also brought

00:00:32.009 --> 00:00:34.310
universal health care to the
city of San Francisco.

00:00:34.310 --> 00:00:38.500
And also, he's been twice
awarded the Most Greenest

00:00:38.500 --> 00:00:40.530
Mayor in America, which
is a big deal.

00:00:40.530 --> 00:00:41.460
GAVIN NEWSOM: Thanks.

00:00:41.460 --> 00:00:42.760
MATTHEW: But we'll here to talk
about "Citizenville,"

00:00:42.760 --> 00:00:44.530
which is his book that
just came out.

00:00:44.530 --> 00:00:46.960
And basically, I want to start
off-- we actually met before

00:00:46.960 --> 00:00:48.700
when you were in the process
of putting together the

00:00:48.700 --> 00:00:49.790
background on this.

00:00:49.790 --> 00:00:52.330
And what actually brought
you to write this book?

00:00:52.330 --> 00:00:53.900
Why did you feel the need
to bring technology and

00:00:53.900 --> 00:00:54.580
government together?

00:00:54.580 --> 00:00:56.060
GAVIN NEWSOM: Well, frustration,
my own

00:00:56.060 --> 00:01:00.550
experiences, the reality that
California, in particular,

00:01:00.550 --> 00:01:02.640
when it comes to technology
and governing is on the

00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:06.080
leading and cutting
edge of 1973.

00:01:06.080 --> 00:01:09.470
And by the way, I literally am
not exaggerating that and I'll

00:01:09.470 --> 00:01:11.110
amplify that point
in a moment.

00:01:11.110 --> 00:01:14.800
But also, my own experience
using the tools of technology

00:01:14.800 --> 00:01:18.910
relatively well to get elected,
to amplify people's

00:01:18.910 --> 00:01:21.910
voices, to democratize a
conversation, to engage in a

00:01:21.910 --> 00:01:25.070
two-way conversation, to get
you to show up and not only

00:01:25.070 --> 00:01:27.610
vote but volunteer,
write a check.

00:01:27.610 --> 00:01:29.500
And then when the election
was over, we'd

00:01:29.500 --> 00:01:30.590
turn off those voices.

00:01:30.590 --> 00:01:33.850
And we'd broadcast for four
years, whereas Matthew and I

00:01:33.850 --> 00:01:36.440
were just saying, three, three
and a half until the election

00:01:36.440 --> 00:01:39.460
starts over again, and
then we engage you.

00:01:39.460 --> 00:01:44.640
My own experience reflecting
on the extraordinary 2008

00:01:44.640 --> 00:01:45.560
Obama campaign.

00:01:45.560 --> 00:01:47.970
The My Barack Obama effort.

00:01:47.970 --> 00:01:51.730
35,000 self-organizing
communities coming together

00:01:51.730 --> 00:01:54.390
and this remarkable opportunity
to, as the

00:01:54.390 --> 00:01:56.570
president said, not just
change the players in

00:01:56.570 --> 00:01:59.110
Washington, DC, but to
change the game.

00:01:59.110 --> 00:02:03.430
And his effort to continue to
engage those communities

00:02:03.430 --> 00:02:07.986
infamously through a platform
called change.gov.

00:02:07.986 --> 00:02:11.910
And he engaged folks famously
or infamously in a

00:02:11.910 --> 00:02:15.700
conversation that didn't end so
well from the president's

00:02:15.700 --> 00:02:16.290
perspective.

00:02:16.290 --> 00:02:19.790
He invited people, these
communities, to come together,

00:02:19.790 --> 00:02:22.260
to continue to have their voices
heard and participate

00:02:22.260 --> 00:02:24.430
in now governing not
just campaigning.

00:02:24.430 --> 00:02:28.900
He created this framework and
encouraged people to say

00:02:28.900 --> 00:02:30.060
what's on their mind.

00:02:30.060 --> 00:02:33.850
What's your number 1, 2, 3, 4
issues first 100 days of my

00:02:33.850 --> 00:02:34.650
administration?

00:02:34.650 --> 00:02:35.560
Is it the war in Iraq?

00:02:35.560 --> 00:02:38.350
It's the war in Afghanistan, war
on terror, climate change

00:02:38.350 --> 00:02:40.190
issues, the financial
meltdown.

00:02:40.190 --> 00:02:41.610
What's on your mind?

00:02:41.610 --> 00:02:44.400
And just as Michelle Obama did
two weeks ago at the Academy

00:02:44.400 --> 00:02:48.780
Awards, he came out in a town
hall with people physically

00:02:48.780 --> 00:02:52.310
there and virtually there
and-- envelope, please--

00:02:52.310 --> 00:02:55.620
unveiled the number one priority
on people's minds in

00:02:55.620 --> 00:02:59.120
the United States of America in
2008, just days before the

00:02:59.120 --> 00:03:00.440
transition was complete.

00:03:00.440 --> 00:03:01.970
And what was it?

00:03:01.970 --> 00:03:02.510
MATTHEW: Legalize pot.

00:03:02.510 --> 00:03:04.660
GAVIN NEWSOM: Legalizing
marijuana.

00:03:04.660 --> 00:03:08.090
And the president
infamously was--

00:03:08.090 --> 00:03:10.960
well, he had a flippant
response.

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:12.990
And the online community
did not take well to

00:03:12.990 --> 00:03:14.130
that flippant response.

00:03:14.130 --> 00:03:15.280
And as a consequence--

00:03:15.280 --> 00:03:16.130
Google it--

00:03:16.130 --> 00:03:17.930
see what happened
to change.gov.

00:03:17.930 --> 00:03:20.400
It went back for
reconstruction.

00:03:20.400 --> 00:03:22.950
It ultimately was transitioned
to the White House website.

00:03:22.950 --> 00:03:26.390
The point being it's not easy
to engage in that two-way

00:03:26.390 --> 00:03:29.340
conversation because it might
not necessarily go in a

00:03:29.340 --> 00:03:31.880
direction that you
want it to go.

00:03:31.880 --> 00:03:34.540
And so this book is really about
an exploration to bridge

00:03:34.540 --> 00:03:37.480
that gap and to begin to address
the issue of governing

00:03:37.480 --> 00:03:40.820
effectively with technology
and having two-way

00:03:40.820 --> 00:03:45.290
conversations with citizens
and engaging in active

00:03:45.290 --> 00:03:48.810
citizenship as opposed to
citizenship that, from my

00:03:48.810 --> 00:03:51.315
perspective, exists today where
we, frankly, treat you

00:03:51.315 --> 00:03:52.480
as subjects.

00:03:52.480 --> 00:03:55.270
Where we do things to you,
but we don't necessarily

00:03:55.270 --> 00:03:57.130
do things with you.

00:03:57.130 --> 00:03:57.820
MATTHEW: That's a good theme.

00:03:57.820 --> 00:03:59.585
I think we talked before about
everyday democracy.

00:03:59.585 --> 00:04:01.550
And after the election's
over, both the

00:04:01.550 --> 00:04:02.990
electorate is kind of exhausted.

00:04:02.990 --> 00:04:05.510
I think we all were after this
last one, as well as the

00:04:05.510 --> 00:04:07.440
politicians when they go back
to their job and actually

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:08.570
getting things done.

00:04:08.570 --> 00:04:11.280
However, that seems like
an old-fashioned model.

00:04:11.280 --> 00:04:12.660
So how do we have everyday
democracy?

00:04:12.660 --> 00:04:15.640
People are very busy and only
the extremists on both sides

00:04:15.640 --> 00:04:17.800
will really take active voice
and get involved.

00:04:17.800 --> 00:04:21.544
And what kind of tools or ways
can we work to bring people in

00:04:21.544 --> 00:04:24.170
an everyday basis, to get their
opinions brought in, in

00:04:24.170 --> 00:04:25.460
a constructive way though,
so we're not

00:04:25.460 --> 00:04:27.440
just ranting and just--

00:04:27.440 --> 00:04:29.780
the town hall, for example, as a
metaphor is maybe a bad one.

00:04:29.780 --> 00:04:32.330
When you think about town halls
usually, some radical--

00:04:32.330 --> 00:04:33.950
you've been to lots
of town halls.

00:04:33.950 --> 00:04:35.590
And so you get the person who
wants to come up to the

00:04:35.590 --> 00:04:37.510
microphone and just complain
about this or that.

00:04:37.510 --> 00:04:39.520
It's not always the most
important issue of the day.

00:04:39.520 --> 00:04:41.620
GAVIN NEWSOM: And that's the
king of the hill concern.

00:04:41.620 --> 00:04:44.230
And that's what happened
frankly, with change.gov.

00:04:44.230 --> 00:04:46.740
The loudest voices organized
and won.

00:04:46.740 --> 00:04:48.260
Marijuana being the
dominant issue.

00:04:48.260 --> 00:04:50.610
What about the other issues that
the president rightfully

00:04:50.610 --> 00:04:52.540
noted were significant
as well?

00:04:52.540 --> 00:04:55.390
And you see that in the physical
world in town halls

00:04:55.390 --> 00:04:57.870
that we have all the time where
we claim that's real

00:04:57.870 --> 00:04:58.480
engagement.

00:04:58.480 --> 00:05:01.480
And we have a budget town hall
where-- truly, I just come

00:05:01.480 --> 00:05:04.070
from my experience as mayor
where we had $6.--

00:05:04.070 --> 00:05:07.810
almost $7 billion budgets, Of
which the entire debate for

00:05:07.810 --> 00:05:11.020
two or three months was around
$20, $25 million.

00:05:11.020 --> 00:05:14.070
So talk about a budget that's
baked before we

00:05:14.070 --> 00:05:15.020
reach out to you.

00:05:15.020 --> 00:05:18.970
That's 99.9% of the budget's
already been done and we're

00:05:18.970 --> 00:05:21.770
having a big debate
about 0.1%.

00:05:21.770 --> 00:05:23.230
And that's public outreach.

00:05:23.230 --> 00:05:25.750
That's participatory budgeting
as we know it.

00:05:25.750 --> 00:05:29.090
And who shows up at those town
halls if you have the time?

00:05:29.090 --> 00:05:30.570
Usually, the persuasion
industry.

00:05:30.570 --> 00:05:32.580
The special interest, folks
with stickers, literally,

00:05:32.580 --> 00:05:33.920
would take over those
town halls.

00:05:33.920 --> 00:05:35.880
And if you've been to them, you
sit in the back and you

00:05:35.880 --> 00:05:36.900
go, I got to get out of here.

00:05:36.900 --> 00:05:38.690
I can't participate in this.

00:05:38.690 --> 00:05:42.040
And so how do we create a
framework where we can have

00:05:42.040 --> 00:05:44.250
civil civic engagement?

00:05:44.250 --> 00:05:47.410
And how can we use these tools
and technology to create that

00:05:47.410 --> 00:05:49.200
platform of engagement
differently?

00:05:49.200 --> 00:05:51.670
And that's what I begin to
explore in this book as I

00:05:51.670 --> 00:05:55.030
physically and virtually
traveled across this country

00:05:55.030 --> 00:05:58.730
in cities and towns large and
small and looked at what

00:05:58.730 --> 00:06:01.670
particularly mayors were doing,
city administrators,

00:06:01.670 --> 00:06:02.850
and local government
was doing.

00:06:02.850 --> 00:06:05.520
Because I've come to conclude
this, my bias being

00:06:05.520 --> 00:06:08.600
self-evident coming from local
government, now of course in

00:06:08.600 --> 00:06:09.400
state government.

00:06:09.400 --> 00:06:11.360
But my by still remains local.

00:06:11.360 --> 00:06:12.780
If you don't like the way the
world looks when you're

00:06:12.780 --> 00:06:15.590
standing up, stand on your
head and go local.

00:06:15.590 --> 00:06:18.990
You'll see remarkable things
happening at the local level.

00:06:18.990 --> 00:06:21.980
One thing I think you all will
agree is proximity confers

00:06:21.980 --> 00:06:23.940
some legitimacy.

00:06:23.940 --> 00:06:27.130
And we tend to view local
government as a little bit

00:06:27.130 --> 00:06:28.410
more responsive.

00:06:28.410 --> 00:06:31.480
We may be driven to frustration
by our local

00:06:31.480 --> 00:06:34.440
elected officials, but they
tend to be a little more

00:06:34.440 --> 00:06:37.920
responsive than state and
certainly federal officials.

00:06:37.920 --> 00:06:39.610
And a little less ideological.

00:06:39.610 --> 00:06:43.290
I said this long as mayor and
as a candidate for mayor.

00:06:43.290 --> 00:06:45.400
Mayors make lousy ideologues
and ideologues

00:06:45.400 --> 00:06:47.480
make terrible mayors.

00:06:47.480 --> 00:06:50.160
But boy, you go to the federal
level, there's a Republican

00:06:50.160 --> 00:06:52.810
plan for Social Security reform
and a Democratic plan

00:06:52.810 --> 00:06:54.020
for Social Security reform.

00:06:54.020 --> 00:06:56.390
State level, there's an economic
development plan

00:06:56.390 --> 00:06:58.320
coming from the Democratic
Party and an economic

00:06:58.320 --> 00:07:00.050
development plan coming from
the Republican Party.

00:07:00.050 --> 00:07:03.480
If I, as mayor, came out with a
Democratic plan for graffiti

00:07:03.480 --> 00:07:05.590
removal, people would roll their
eyes and say, what the

00:07:05.590 --> 00:07:07.150
heck's this guy talking about?

00:07:07.150 --> 00:07:09.340
Just clean up the damn
graffiti, mayor.

00:07:09.340 --> 00:07:09.890
Get it done.

00:07:09.890 --> 00:07:13.860
So there is more of an
orientation of results and

00:07:13.860 --> 00:07:15.650
less tribalism.

00:07:15.650 --> 00:07:18.850
And so local government tends,
from my perspective, to be the

00:07:18.850 --> 00:07:22.750
most effective of all forms of
governance as it relates to

00:07:22.750 --> 00:07:24.350
solutions and an
entrepreneurial

00:07:24.350 --> 00:07:25.630
framework of thinking.

00:07:25.630 --> 00:07:27.440
And therein lies some
of the answers

00:07:27.440 --> 00:07:28.400
to Matthew's questions.

00:07:28.400 --> 00:07:32.000
And in the book, we lay out
some very specific and

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:34.900
promising examples of where
this kind of Socratic

00:07:34.900 --> 00:07:38.620
engagement is happening where
those extreme voices are

00:07:38.620 --> 00:07:40.720
becoming less and
less relevant.

00:07:40.720 --> 00:07:43.320
MATTHEW: One of the things you
have is about the role of data

00:07:43.320 --> 00:07:46.060
in all this, and how that's one
of the key-- you use the

00:07:46.060 --> 00:07:48.820
word "absolute transparency,"
which is a pretty big

00:07:48.820 --> 00:07:50.360
statement, absolute anything
in politics.

00:07:50.360 --> 00:07:52.050
And you did caveat that a little
bit by saying, because

00:07:52.050 --> 00:07:54.450
there's obviously
privacy issues.

00:07:54.450 --> 00:07:56.110
There's issues of security.

00:07:56.110 --> 00:07:57.650
And you also talk about
WikiLeaks a little bit as

00:07:57.650 --> 00:07:58.330
being an example.

00:07:58.330 --> 00:08:01.550
There are some outside
limitations, implications to

00:08:01.550 --> 00:08:03.020
absolute transparency.

00:08:03.020 --> 00:08:05.160
We were just talking about
that briefly before.

00:08:05.160 --> 00:08:06.200
So how do we do this properly?

00:08:06.200 --> 00:08:07.950
How do we say everything
should be transparent?

00:08:07.950 --> 00:08:09.360
All data should be out there?

00:08:09.360 --> 00:08:11.680
Because you know, as you
mentioned over and over, it's

00:08:11.680 --> 00:08:14.910
true, that the bureaucrats will
always withhold data.

00:08:14.910 --> 00:08:16.370
There's no reason to
get that out there.

00:08:16.370 --> 00:08:18.280
You only get skewered
by the press.

00:08:18.280 --> 00:08:21.510
You lay yourself out to be
attacked and we don't have an

00:08:21.510 --> 00:08:23.630
environment that is
very promising or

00:08:23.630 --> 00:08:24.410
conducive to that.

00:08:24.410 --> 00:08:25.340
GAVIN NEWSOM: Well,
our default--

00:08:25.340 --> 00:08:26.730
and this is a great struggle.

00:08:26.730 --> 00:08:28.890
And I don't have the perfect
answer because I don't think

00:08:28.890 --> 00:08:31.780
it exists on the issue of
privacy and transparency.

00:08:31.780 --> 00:08:34.590
But one thing I do have is a
little bit experience and that

00:08:34.590 --> 00:08:36.919
is the default for elected
officials and government

00:08:36.919 --> 00:08:39.510
officials is secrecy, period.

00:08:39.510 --> 00:08:41.799
Just look at the debate we're
having, literally raging

00:08:41.799 --> 00:08:44.650
today, in the wee hours last
night in a filibuster over

00:08:44.650 --> 00:08:47.930
John Brennan's confirmation and
Paul arguing around the

00:08:47.930 --> 00:08:49.040
drone policy.

00:08:49.040 --> 00:08:52.400
And the quote unquote, "memos" a
lack of transparency are the

00:08:52.400 --> 00:08:55.630
same relating to the ready,
fire, aim kill list policy and

00:08:55.630 --> 00:08:58.340
the due process concerns
around drone strikes of

00:08:58.340 --> 00:09:01.150
American citizens that are
legitimate concerns.

00:09:01.150 --> 00:09:04.220
Even the most quote unquote,
"self-declared or

00:09:04.220 --> 00:09:08.460
self-described" transparent
president, the most

00:09:08.460 --> 00:09:11.410
transparent in our history,
President Obama, is still

00:09:11.410 --> 00:09:15.010
struggling with this idea of
transparency as it relates to

00:09:15.010 --> 00:09:16.930
legal justification of
these drone strikes.

00:09:16.930 --> 00:09:20.060
So this is easy to orient
around your rhetoric.

00:09:20.060 --> 00:09:22.740
It's difficult to practice
in reality.

00:09:22.740 --> 00:09:24.770
My experience has,
interestingly, come right back

00:09:24.770 --> 00:09:26.290
here to Google.

00:09:26.290 --> 00:09:29.010
And in the book, I talk about
some of the early work we were

00:09:29.010 --> 00:09:32.430
doing on Wi-Fi together that
didn't necessarily work out,

00:09:32.430 --> 00:09:34.350
free Wi-Fi in San Francisco.

00:09:34.350 --> 00:09:37.520
And some of the correspondence
I had with your two founders,

00:09:37.520 --> 00:09:41.520
Larry and Sergey, and the emails
that the press got

00:09:41.520 --> 00:09:44.390
their hands on through the
Freedom of Information Act.

00:09:44.390 --> 00:09:48.360
And they put, literally,
infamously, two-page bleeding

00:09:48.360 --> 00:09:51.920
story, front page, screaming
headline in the "San Francisco

00:09:51.920 --> 00:09:55.860
Chronicle" with actual photos
of the copies of the email

00:09:55.860 --> 00:09:57.350
about absolutely nothing.

00:09:57.350 --> 00:10:00.270
But you look at it and you go,
my gosh, some big scandal

00:10:00.270 --> 00:10:01.870
between Google and the city.

00:10:01.870 --> 00:10:04.610
And there literally was nothing,
but it was a fury of

00:10:04.610 --> 00:10:07.510
wanting to get that information
and access that

00:10:07.510 --> 00:10:08.390
created this desire.

00:10:08.390 --> 00:10:12.140
And my response was, well, I'm
getting rid of my email.

00:10:12.140 --> 00:10:15.420
And I literally no longer
emailed anyone after that

00:10:15.420 --> 00:10:17.110
because it was a
got you frame.

00:10:17.110 --> 00:10:19.800
The press wanted to do
it to play gotcha.

00:10:19.800 --> 00:10:22.910
And that's the frame that makes
us less willing to give

00:10:22.910 --> 00:10:25.800
information up except
the basic minimum.

00:10:25.800 --> 00:10:28.040
I'm not saying that's the right
thing, and I encourage

00:10:28.040 --> 00:10:29.900
the press to continue
to do that.

00:10:29.900 --> 00:10:32.290
But my argument in this
book is we're living

00:10:32.290 --> 00:10:34.500
in a world of WikiLeaks.

00:10:34.500 --> 00:10:36.570
We're living in a glass
neighborhood.

00:10:36.570 --> 00:10:40.180
You understand this better than
anybody as it relates to

00:10:40.180 --> 00:10:41.560
the issues of privacy.

00:10:41.560 --> 00:10:44.580
And we're going to have to, if
we're going to build trust

00:10:44.580 --> 00:10:48.500
with the public, have to have
a default of openness.

00:10:48.500 --> 00:10:53.010
And data is profound from my
perspective in this context.

00:10:53.010 --> 00:10:56.430
It's not just about a mayor's
schedule or an elected

00:10:56.430 --> 00:10:58.200
official's contacts.

00:10:58.200 --> 00:10:59.070
And that's trivial.

00:10:59.070 --> 00:11:02.080
That's the "US Weekly" version
of transparency.

00:11:02.080 --> 00:11:04.050
That's just pure interest.

00:11:04.050 --> 00:11:05.980
It's the substance that's
happening in government

00:11:05.980 --> 00:11:08.690
agencies, locally at your
recreation and parks

00:11:08.690 --> 00:11:12.290
department, the library system,
state-wide at the DMV,

00:11:12.290 --> 00:11:16.150
or big planning commissions,
what's happening federally in

00:11:16.150 --> 00:11:18.720
large agencies at Health
and Human Services.

00:11:18.720 --> 00:11:22.310
And for us to bring that data
to the light of day in a

00:11:22.310 --> 00:11:24.780
machine-readable downloadable
way,

00:11:24.780 --> 00:11:27.080
remarkable things can happen.

00:11:27.080 --> 00:11:30.890
And that's what is taking shape
across this country as

00:11:30.890 --> 00:11:33.440
this open data movement's
beginning to form.

00:11:33.440 --> 00:11:35.270
And I was, as mayor,
one of the first--

00:11:35.270 --> 00:11:37.290
I think I was the first
mayor in the country--

00:11:37.290 --> 00:11:40.260
to establish an open data
requirement for data sets.

00:11:40.260 --> 00:11:44.720
And within literally hours of
putting these up, we had apps

00:11:44.720 --> 00:11:47.610
that were created by third-party
developers that we

00:11:47.610 --> 00:11:50.280
could have never imagined as
government officials the

00:11:50.280 --> 00:11:53.050
importance of putting together
that cost us nothing.

00:11:53.050 --> 00:11:55.470
Crime data we put out
and all of a sudden

00:11:55.470 --> 00:11:56.790
these crime maps occurred.

00:11:56.790 --> 00:11:59.480
Transit data and all these
remarkable transit apps.

00:11:59.480 --> 00:12:03.190
And we literally created an app
store for not the Android

00:12:03.190 --> 00:12:06.240
platform, but in this case for
our own city services.

00:12:06.240 --> 00:12:07.990
And we started working with
other mayors across the

00:12:07.990 --> 00:12:10.790
country through open APIs
and others to begin

00:12:10.790 --> 00:12:12.180
to do the same thing.

00:12:12.180 --> 00:12:14.040
And it started making
me think, wow, what

00:12:14.040 --> 00:12:15.620
else can we put up?

00:12:15.620 --> 00:12:18.870
And what else can the private
sector mash up and see things

00:12:18.870 --> 00:12:20.770
that we never could see?

00:12:20.770 --> 00:12:23.330
And of course, afford things we
never could afford through

00:12:23.330 --> 00:12:26.915
the traditional multi-year
procurement process.

00:12:26.915 --> 00:12:28.960
MATTHEW: You bring a lot of
good examples of people,

00:12:28.960 --> 00:12:31.580
actually individuals, taking
this data and putting it to

00:12:31.580 --> 00:12:33.480
good use, like crime statistics
or homeless

00:12:33.480 --> 00:12:35.570
statistics, t hat
sort of thing.

00:12:35.570 --> 00:12:38.450
Why is there not more of
a for-profit ecosystem?

00:12:38.450 --> 00:12:39.670
You mentioned the [INAUDIBLE]

00:12:39.670 --> 00:12:43.240
idea about creating an incubator
for businesses that

00:12:43.240 --> 00:12:45.240
take data from the public
sources and make

00:12:45.240 --> 00:12:46.370
businesses around it.

00:12:46.370 --> 00:12:47.580
Because it seems like there's
lots of people doing

00:12:47.580 --> 00:12:48.080
experiments.

00:12:48.080 --> 00:12:50.810
There lots of not-for-profit
work.

00:12:50.810 --> 00:12:53.490
But to do things at scale and
sustain itself, it seems like

00:12:53.490 --> 00:12:55.030
there needs to be more
for-profit models around it.

00:12:55.030 --> 00:12:56.230
GAVIN NEWSOM: And I think you're
starting to see that.

00:12:56.230 --> 00:12:57.800
I mean, you're starting to see,
particularly in the crime

00:12:57.800 --> 00:13:00.520
mapping technology, folks are
starting to scale that and

00:13:00.520 --> 00:13:03.340
basically sell out that
technology, the more premium,

00:13:03.340 --> 00:13:06.260
the freemium models in other
cities across the country.

00:13:06.260 --> 00:13:07.200
So I think you're
just starting to

00:13:07.200 --> 00:13:08.160
see this take shape.

00:13:08.160 --> 00:13:10.490
But it's the quality
of the data.

00:13:10.490 --> 00:13:12.510
I mean, we're still scraping
that data.

00:13:12.510 --> 00:13:14.270
We're not providing
all that raw data.

00:13:14.270 --> 00:13:15.690
We're still curating it.

00:13:15.690 --> 00:13:17.960
And my argument is we need to
do what, interestingly,

00:13:17.960 --> 00:13:20.780
President Reagan did in the
'80s with satellite

00:13:20.780 --> 00:13:25.115
technology, of which this
company in particular has been

00:13:25.115 --> 00:13:29.150
the lion share beneficiary of
monetizing that data, which

00:13:29.150 --> 00:13:30.370
used to just be ours.

00:13:30.370 --> 00:13:32.320
It used to be meaning
yours as taxpayers.

00:13:32.320 --> 00:13:35.660
But it was held in federal
agencies like NOAA.

00:13:35.660 --> 00:13:40.530
And that data was just held
there in the vaults, until in

00:13:40.530 --> 00:13:44.290
the '80s they decided to open
up that platform and gave us

00:13:44.290 --> 00:13:48.340
AccuWeather, gave us Google
Maps, gave us GPS, and all of

00:13:48.340 --> 00:13:49.110
these wonderful things.

00:13:49.110 --> 00:13:51.940
And millions of jobs have been
created, billions of wealth

00:13:51.940 --> 00:13:55.140
have been created because of
that open data effort.

00:13:55.140 --> 00:13:58.160
What else is sitting in the
vaults of government that you

00:13:58.160 --> 00:14:01.290
can mash up, monetize,
and re-imagine?

00:14:01.290 --> 00:14:04.320
And it's limitless the things
that have been stored for

00:14:04.320 --> 00:14:08.590
decades, for a century in
governments large and small

00:14:08.590 --> 00:14:10.240
all across, not only California

00:14:10.240 --> 00:14:11.380
but across this country.

00:14:11.380 --> 00:14:13.860
And so that's what
I'm arguing for.

00:14:13.860 --> 00:14:16.890
It's difficult though, because
we hold off the issues of

00:14:16.890 --> 00:14:19.280
privacy as it relates
being unwilling to

00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:20.490
provide certain data.

00:14:20.490 --> 00:14:22.660
Again, the default.

00:14:22.660 --> 00:14:25.220
And that's our struggle,
is what's appropriate?

00:14:25.220 --> 00:14:27.100
It's not personnel
files, per se.

00:14:27.100 --> 00:14:28.680
But it's certainly everyone's
salary.

00:14:28.680 --> 00:14:30.140
You have a right to know that.

00:14:30.140 --> 00:14:31.190
We're struggling with that.

00:14:31.190 --> 00:14:33.195
People don't want to necessarily
know that you know

00:14:33.195 --> 00:14:36.340
their salary behind the
counter at the DMV.

00:14:36.340 --> 00:14:39.140
But they're public servants
and it seems you

00:14:39.140 --> 00:14:40.370
have a right to know.

00:14:40.370 --> 00:14:42.520
But do you have a right to
know their disciplinary

00:14:42.520 --> 00:14:45.010
records or their performance
reviews?

00:14:45.010 --> 00:14:47.280
And therein lies
that friction.

00:14:47.280 --> 00:14:48.820
And so that's what we're
all struggling with.

00:14:48.820 --> 00:14:49.810
MATTHEW: Sure.

00:14:49.810 --> 00:14:51.510
I think, actually from a Google
perspective, we're

00:14:51.510 --> 00:14:53.490
trying to-- obviously, the data
being made available to

00:14:53.490 --> 00:14:55.450
everybody in the world so we can
help make it available to

00:14:55.450 --> 00:14:58.200
people, make it useful to
people would be great.

00:14:58.200 --> 00:15:00.580
Is there a way of doing this
or going down this path

00:15:00.580 --> 00:15:02.670
without sounding like
an ideological idea?

00:15:02.670 --> 00:15:05.180
I know you're saying you're not
an ideologue about this.

00:15:05.180 --> 00:15:07.160
But to some degree, you're
saying government should get

00:15:07.160 --> 00:15:08.270
out the business of doing
some of this.

00:15:08.270 --> 00:15:09.520
And basically, get the data
out there and let

00:15:09.520 --> 00:15:10.640
other people do it.

00:15:10.640 --> 00:15:12.470
And to some degree, we're saying
that means probably the

00:15:12.470 --> 00:15:15.820
government's doing less, or can
do other things-- be free

00:15:15.820 --> 00:15:16.920
to do other things.

00:15:16.920 --> 00:15:20.300
And do we get ourselves caught
in that kind of debate

00:15:20.300 --> 00:15:21.650
inadvertently?

00:15:21.650 --> 00:15:23.610
It's an issue for us as well
as a company of course.

00:15:23.610 --> 00:15:26.030
GAVIN NEWSOM: Brilliant
question.

00:15:26.030 --> 00:15:26.370
It's interesting.

00:15:26.370 --> 00:15:27.830
A couple years ago I
was re-reading--

00:15:27.830 --> 00:15:29.820
in anticipation of the
president's last state of the

00:15:29.820 --> 00:15:32.420
union, it's always fun to read
previous states of the union.

00:15:32.420 --> 00:15:35.210
Also, it's a great way to
measure success in terms of

00:15:35.210 --> 00:15:37.360
promises made and
promises kept.

00:15:37.360 --> 00:15:39.840
And a few years ago, the
president had a wonderful--

00:15:39.840 --> 00:15:41.600
every year we have
in politics--

00:15:41.600 --> 00:15:44.170
politicians are good at this--
we have our themes.

00:15:44.170 --> 00:15:46.060
And his was "win the future."

00:15:46.060 --> 00:15:47.490
And I remember, this was
three years ago.

00:15:47.490 --> 00:15:48.710
He said, you can't win
the future with a

00:15:48.710 --> 00:15:49.595
government of the past.

00:15:49.595 --> 00:15:51.370
And I'm applauding at least.

00:15:51.370 --> 00:15:53.610
And he said, we have 15 agencies
that are responsible

00:15:53.610 --> 00:15:57.740
for exports, 5 responsible
for housing policy.

00:15:57.740 --> 00:16:00.630
And my favorite, he
says, is salmon.

00:16:00.630 --> 00:16:02.780
We have the Department of
Interior that's responsible

00:16:02.780 --> 00:16:05.490
for salmon as it relates
to freshwater.

00:16:05.490 --> 00:16:07.690
But right when they make their
way out to see, it's the

00:16:07.690 --> 00:16:09.900
Department of Commerce
that's responsible

00:16:09.900 --> 00:16:10.830
for those same salmon.

00:16:10.830 --> 00:16:14.720
We cannot win the future with
a government of the past.

00:16:14.720 --> 00:16:19.930
And he was making an argument to
modernize government and to

00:16:19.930 --> 00:16:21.180
become more responsive
and effective.

00:16:21.180 --> 00:16:23.330
But he then went on to say
something that I thought

00:16:23.330 --> 00:16:25.820
rather remarkable for
a Democrat to say.

00:16:25.820 --> 00:16:28.350
He quoted Lincoln, this was
before we all started quoting

00:16:28.350 --> 00:16:29.600
Lincoln after the movie.

00:16:32.380 --> 00:16:35.660
And he said, and I subscribe to
President Lincoln's point

00:16:35.660 --> 00:16:39.410
of view that government should
do nothing more than what

00:16:39.410 --> 00:16:43.150
individuals can do better
for themselves.

00:16:43.150 --> 00:16:45.600
And for a Democrat to say
that, didn't get any

00:16:45.600 --> 00:16:48.290
attention, I thought
rather profound.

00:16:48.290 --> 00:16:52.150
That's something you would
expect a conservative to say.

00:16:52.150 --> 00:16:57.030
And I believe his sincerity
about that in terms of

00:16:57.030 --> 00:16:58.060
approaching things like that.

00:16:58.060 --> 00:17:01.650
I think now more than ever in
the era of austerity where

00:17:01.650 --> 00:17:04.150
we're dealing with, I think, the
three greatest challenges

00:17:04.150 --> 00:17:06.380
that will dominate the next 10
years-- the merger of IT and

00:17:06.380 --> 00:17:08.920
globalization, the issues of
debt and entitlement, and

00:17:08.920 --> 00:17:11.700
energy and climate change and
the impact that will have--

00:17:11.700 --> 00:17:14.990
that this is a debate
worth having.

00:17:14.990 --> 00:17:18.280
And my framework is the old
Donald Kettl framework, a

00:17:18.280 --> 00:17:20.410
political scientist who
made this argument and

00:17:20.410 --> 00:17:21.410
observation years ago.

00:17:21.410 --> 00:17:24.463
Tim O'Reilly popularized it.

00:17:24.463 --> 00:17:26.819
And he's right, the government
today operates more like a

00:17:26.819 --> 00:17:30.530
vending machine where you put
in your dollar taxes and you

00:17:30.530 --> 00:17:33.720
get limited or finite choices--
police, fire, health

00:17:33.720 --> 00:17:35.490
care, education, national
offense.

00:17:35.490 --> 00:17:36.830
And if you don't like
what you get--

00:17:36.830 --> 00:17:37.760
you've all done it--

00:17:37.760 --> 00:17:38.770
what do we do?

00:17:38.770 --> 00:17:40.440
We shake the machine.

00:17:40.440 --> 00:17:41.350
We kick the machine.

00:17:41.350 --> 00:17:42.050
We protest--

00:17:42.050 --> 00:17:45.120
Occupy Movement, Tea Party,
whatever it may be.

00:17:45.120 --> 00:17:48.010
And not thinking from that
framework of scarcity any

00:17:48.010 --> 00:17:50.620
longer, this machine thinking.

00:17:50.620 --> 00:17:54.910
Again, the you vote,
I decide model.

00:17:54.910 --> 00:17:58.060
To a framework of the
platform, the

00:17:58.060 --> 00:18:00.000
smartphone, the Android.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:03.610
The idea that you didn't develop
700,000 plus apps for

00:18:03.610 --> 00:18:05.140
the Android platform.

00:18:05.140 --> 00:18:07.310
You've partnered with
millions of people.

00:18:07.310 --> 00:18:09.550
And as a consequence, they've
come up with creative

00:18:09.550 --> 00:18:11.680
solutions and ideas that
Google could never--

00:18:11.680 --> 00:18:13.740
you guys could never
have imagined.

00:18:13.740 --> 00:18:16.970
Why not operate government
accordingly as a platform, a

00:18:16.970 --> 00:18:18.690
convener, a coordinator?

00:18:18.690 --> 00:18:20.710
A cultivator, sure.

00:18:20.710 --> 00:18:24.540
To be, as my friend Eric
[INAUDIBLE] says, "big on what

00:18:24.540 --> 00:18:28.780
but small on how." Less
prescriptive on how we

00:18:28.780 --> 00:18:32.100
actually program solutions, but
committed nonetheless to

00:18:32.100 --> 00:18:33.900
dealing with big issues
like ignorance

00:18:33.900 --> 00:18:35.730
and poverty and disease.

00:18:35.730 --> 00:18:38.100
And use these tools of
technology that you are

00:18:38.100 --> 00:18:43.770
creating in real time to
democratize, amplify, voices.

00:18:43.770 --> 00:18:45.240
Because one thing I've learned--
it's the old Bill

00:18:45.240 --> 00:18:46.695
Joy's law in Sun Microsystems.

00:18:46.695 --> 00:18:49.400
He says, no matter who you are,
no matter how good you

00:18:49.400 --> 00:18:52.460
think you are as an
organization, the smartest

00:18:52.460 --> 00:18:55.000
people work for someone else.

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:58.400
This idea that none of us are
experts in everything, but all

00:18:58.400 --> 00:19:00.670
of us are an expert
in something.

00:19:00.670 --> 00:19:03.940
How can we connect to that
remarkable capacity

00:19:03.940 --> 00:19:06.570
intelligence that exists in
every single one of you and

00:19:06.570 --> 00:19:07.420
network that?

00:19:07.420 --> 00:19:09.250
That notion of the wisdom
of the crowd.

00:19:09.250 --> 00:19:12.050
How can we, as government,
begin to connect that?

00:19:12.050 --> 00:19:14.770
Seven years ago, I couldn't have
imagined we'd be living

00:19:14.770 --> 00:19:18.100
in the world we are today with
these tools of technology that

00:19:18.100 --> 00:19:22.170
allow that possibility
in a profound way.

00:19:22.170 --> 00:19:24.210
Government as a platform.

00:19:24.210 --> 00:19:28.290
Not small, not big, not
ideological on the frame that

00:19:28.290 --> 00:19:29.450
we've engaged.

00:19:29.450 --> 00:19:30.010
But strong?

00:19:30.010 --> 00:19:30.750
Sure.

00:19:30.750 --> 00:19:31.120
Lean?

00:19:31.120 --> 00:19:31.700
Absolutely.

00:19:31.700 --> 00:19:32.240
Limited?

00:19:32.240 --> 00:19:33.290
Fine.

00:19:33.290 --> 00:19:38.300
But strong and impactful in
terms of solving big problems.

00:19:38.300 --> 00:19:39.600
MATTHEW: By the way, we have
microphones here in the

00:19:39.600 --> 00:19:41.470
audience if you want to
line up for questions.

00:19:41.470 --> 00:19:43.770
But I will take some from
the audience as well.

00:19:43.770 --> 00:19:45.570
Let me actually challenge
you on one thing.

00:19:45.570 --> 00:19:46.840
One of the themes in your
book I thought was

00:19:46.840 --> 00:19:49.880
harder to kind of accept.

00:19:49.880 --> 00:19:51.930
GAVIN NEWSOM: I'll take some
tea as I think about what

00:19:51.930 --> 00:19:52.590
you're going to say.

00:19:52.590 --> 00:19:54.580
MATTHEW: So the idea that you
want to bring innovation into

00:19:54.580 --> 00:19:54.850
government.

00:19:54.850 --> 00:19:57.400
I think it's a great idea of
freeing up data and letting

00:19:57.400 --> 00:20:01.540
the outside world kind of play
with it and work with it.

00:20:01.540 --> 00:20:04.020
But I think bring innovation
into government seems like a

00:20:04.020 --> 00:20:04.810
much harder task.

00:20:04.810 --> 00:20:07.460
How to I make government
itself more innovative?

00:20:07.460 --> 00:20:08.570
What's the challenge?

00:20:08.570 --> 00:20:10.800
There's no alternative, they
have a monopoly on power.

00:20:10.800 --> 00:20:12.980
And they are the vending
machine.

00:20:12.980 --> 00:20:14.230
They control the box.

00:20:14.230 --> 00:20:15.530
How do we do this?

00:20:15.530 --> 00:20:17.190
And secondly, you bring up this
idea about needing to

00:20:17.190 --> 00:20:17.960
start from scratch.

00:20:17.960 --> 00:20:20.330
We can't just incrementally
improve a vending machine,

00:20:20.330 --> 00:20:21.440
make a better mechanism.

00:20:21.440 --> 00:20:24.120
We need to be much more
fundamental, like moving to

00:20:24.120 --> 00:20:26.040
the cloud and that
sort of thing.

00:20:26.040 --> 00:20:28.400
Both those things to me feel
like for the government a very

00:20:28.400 --> 00:20:29.300
unlikely thing to happen.

00:20:29.300 --> 00:20:30.185
GAVIN NEWSOM: I get it.

00:20:30.185 --> 00:20:32.080
And trust me, I get it.

00:20:32.080 --> 00:20:35.390
And just very quick for what
it's worth, background.

00:20:35.390 --> 00:20:38.950
I come from the private sector,
but in a very sort of

00:20:38.950 --> 00:20:41.350
physical brick and
mortar world.

00:20:41.350 --> 00:20:42.000
Small businesses.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:44.110
I have about 17 small business,
restaurants, hotels,

00:20:44.110 --> 00:20:46.210
and wineries, about 1,000
employees in the state.

00:20:46.210 --> 00:20:48.350
And I truly say that not to
impress you, but to press upon

00:20:48.350 --> 00:20:51.190
you I've always tried to take
that entrepreneurial energy

00:20:51.190 --> 00:20:54.060
into my work as a county
supervisor, as a mayor, and

00:20:54.060 --> 00:20:55.270
now lieutenant governor.

00:20:55.270 --> 00:20:58.020
And it's extraordinarily
frustrating.

00:20:58.020 --> 00:20:59.440
I don't want to be more
business-like.

00:20:59.440 --> 00:21:01.420
We're not a business.

00:21:01.420 --> 00:21:04.610
But I want to be more iterative
and entrepreneurial.

00:21:04.610 --> 00:21:07.720
And I think we should encourage
some enlightened

00:21:07.720 --> 00:21:08.760
risk-taking in government.

00:21:08.760 --> 00:21:09.780
We are risk adverse.

00:21:09.780 --> 00:21:11.740
We're scared to death at
tomorrow's headlines.

00:21:11.740 --> 00:21:12.510
And so you're absolutely
right.

00:21:12.510 --> 00:21:13.480
It's the right question.

00:21:13.480 --> 00:21:15.330
It's the standard operating
procedure.

00:21:15.330 --> 00:21:16.780
It's a clay layer
of bureaucracy.

00:21:16.780 --> 00:21:18.600
It's a big civil service.

00:21:18.600 --> 00:21:21.610
It's a large bureaucratic,
