00:32:08.720 --> 00:32:10.480
Sky" talking about the
issues of women.

00:32:10.480 --> 00:32:12.530
They just came up with social
games for good.

00:32:12.530 --> 00:32:14.710
And they have a game to
encourage people and to

00:32:14.710 --> 00:32:16.680
educate people about the issue
of women and girls around the

00:32:16.680 --> 00:32:18.190
world in empowerment.

00:32:18.190 --> 00:32:21.680
And so how do we meet people
where they are?

00:32:21.680 --> 00:32:22.740
MATTHEW: Again, let me encourage
people to take the

00:32:22.740 --> 00:32:24.720
microphone if they
have questions.

00:32:24.720 --> 00:32:26.140
I know you didn't talk about
this much in your book, but I

00:32:26.140 --> 00:32:28.555
did want to ask you, how does
this play out internationally?

00:32:28.555 --> 00:32:30.090
You talked mostly, it
seemed like, about

00:32:30.090 --> 00:32:31.436
domestic politics here.

00:32:31.436 --> 00:32:33.490
But what's your view on that?

00:32:33.490 --> 00:32:34.660
GAVIN NEWSOM: It plays
perfectly.

00:32:34.660 --> 00:32:35.130
[INAUDIBLE]

00:32:35.130 --> 00:32:36.650
in Spain, [INAUDIBLE].

00:32:36.650 --> 00:32:38.880
I mean when the microbloggers
in China, quarter

00:32:38.880 --> 00:32:40.090
of a billion folks.

00:32:40.090 --> 00:32:43.820
Chinese government cannot
suppress those voices, even

00:32:43.820 --> 00:32:48.020
though they spend more money
in China to suppress voices

00:32:48.020 --> 00:32:50.240
than they do on national
defense.

00:32:50.240 --> 00:32:51.690
What's happened obviously,
[INAUDIBLE]

00:32:51.690 --> 00:32:52.240
Square.

00:32:52.240 --> 00:32:53.770
It's happened around the
rest of the world.

00:32:53.770 --> 00:32:55.980
It's very real and
very relevant.

00:32:55.980 --> 00:33:00.480
And of course, your own Eric
Schmidt coming out with a book

00:33:00.480 --> 00:33:03.710
to raise that consciousness and
elevate the international

00:33:03.710 --> 00:33:06.695
debate along these same
lines with his book.

00:33:06.695 --> 00:33:09.030
MATTHEW: Let's take some
questions from the audience.

00:33:09.030 --> 00:33:11.000
MALE SPEAKER: So I just came
back from living a few years

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:15.200
in a rather large city, which I
won't mention to prejudices,

00:33:15.200 --> 00:33:17.570
and the trains and subways
are clean.

00:33:17.570 --> 00:33:18.370
They run on time.

00:33:18.370 --> 00:33:19.270
They're not expensive.

00:33:19.270 --> 00:33:21.030
There's no garbage
on the streets.

00:33:21.030 --> 00:33:23.340
The potholes are filled,
et cetera, et cetera.

00:33:23.340 --> 00:33:25.670
And I come back to San Francisco
and I'm trying to

00:33:25.670 --> 00:33:25.930
understand--

00:33:25.930 --> 00:33:29.410
GAVIN NEWSOM: It's changed
since I'm mayor, I know.

00:33:29.410 --> 00:33:31.280
Yes.

00:33:31.280 --> 00:33:32.700
MALE SPEAKER: And the
taxes aren't that

00:33:32.700 --> 00:33:34.090
much higher, either.

00:33:34.090 --> 00:33:36.240
I'm trying to understand how
what you're talking about is

00:33:36.240 --> 00:33:38.810
going to solve those really
basic questions.

00:33:38.810 --> 00:33:41.630
Let's forget about the fancier
ones you're talking about.

00:33:41.630 --> 00:33:44.550
GAVIN NEWSOM: Well, I
mean, substantively.

00:33:44.550 --> 00:33:46.910
I could give you dozens of
examples as it relates to

00:33:46.910 --> 00:33:48.820
issues of homelessness,
potholes.

00:33:48.820 --> 00:33:51.170
I mean, just one example
see, click, fix.

00:33:51.170 --> 00:33:55.630
See a pothole, click it, send
it with the open API we did

00:33:55.630 --> 00:33:57.550
with Twitter to 311
call center in San

00:33:57.550 --> 00:33:58.960
Francisco, fix it.

00:33:58.960 --> 00:34:03.230
Two-way conversation, measured,
mapped, and people

00:34:03.230 --> 00:34:04.240
are empowered.

00:34:04.240 --> 00:34:05.830
Citizens are more engaged.

00:34:05.830 --> 00:34:08.750
And we are held to a higher
level of accountability.

00:34:08.750 --> 00:34:13.320
I can give you dozens of
examples of improved

00:34:13.320 --> 00:34:17.909
efficiency, reduced costs, more
citizen engagement with

00:34:17.909 --> 00:34:20.000
these kinds of tools of
technology that begin to

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:25.050
address the timeliness of buses,
the ability to address

00:34:25.050 --> 00:34:29.360
panhandling, the competency of
our efforts to pave and clean

00:34:29.360 --> 00:34:31.909
streets along the lines
of your question.

00:34:31.909 --> 00:34:33.120
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah, but that
other one I'm talking about

00:34:33.120 --> 00:34:35.250
was put in place by a big
bureaucracy and so

00:34:35.250 --> 00:34:36.940
forth and it worked.

00:34:36.940 --> 00:34:39.120
And I'm saying there's probably
something a whole lot

00:34:39.120 --> 00:34:41.889
more-- and by the way there,
if a train's more than five

00:34:41.889 --> 00:34:44.500
minutes late, they give you a
paper so you can give that at

00:34:44.500 --> 00:34:46.270
the office because that's
how seldom it happens.

00:34:49.040 --> 00:34:52.810
GAVIN NEWSOM: I guess I have
a bias for our form of

00:34:52.810 --> 00:34:55.710
governance as imperfect
as it is.

00:34:55.710 --> 00:35:00.850
I'm with Justice Brandeis that
in a democracy, the most

00:35:00.850 --> 00:35:03.030
important office is the
office of citizen.

00:35:03.030 --> 00:35:05.880
And what I'm arguing for here is
active citizen engagement,

00:35:05.880 --> 00:35:08.610
which with respect to some of
those examples, though I don't

00:35:08.610 --> 00:35:11.560
know yours particularly, I doubt
there's that kind of

00:35:11.560 --> 00:35:13.770
active citizen engagement.

00:35:13.770 --> 00:35:17.230
There's probably more of a
top-down centralized model of

00:35:17.230 --> 00:35:19.870
governance that I don't
necessarily think in the long

00:35:19.870 --> 00:35:22.780
run is going to service
more than just

00:35:22.780 --> 00:35:24.010
getting trains on time.

00:35:24.010 --> 00:35:26.260
It doesn't service the
entrepreneurial passions and

00:35:26.260 --> 00:35:29.270
the innovative spirit that I
think defines the best of our

00:35:29.270 --> 00:35:29.990
region and our state.

00:35:29.990 --> 00:35:31.650
MALE SPEAKER: It was
a democracy.

00:35:31.650 --> 00:35:31.990
GAVIN NEWSOM: Yeah.

00:35:31.990 --> 00:35:34.200
Well, let me also
just concur--

00:35:34.200 --> 00:35:39.910
hell, I was just at the Incheon
Airport in Korea,

00:35:39.910 --> 00:35:42.370
which is one of those airports
you just hope along the lines

00:35:42.370 --> 00:35:46.520
you're arguing that you have
your plane delayed because

00:35:46.520 --> 00:35:51.350
it's got a couple golf courses,
hotel, spa, a museum.

00:35:51.350 --> 00:35:56.840
And I flew from there to LAX,
which literally-- you got my

00:35:56.840 --> 00:35:58.930
point-- is like flying from
the Jetsons to the

00:35:58.930 --> 00:36:00.350
Flintstones.

00:36:00.350 --> 00:36:05.780
So I'm not denying your
example and embracing

00:36:05.780 --> 00:36:08.480
high-speed rail and the
remarkable capacity in

00:36:08.480 --> 00:36:10.690
Singapore and other parts
of the world to

00:36:10.690 --> 00:36:11.620
do wonderful things.

00:36:11.620 --> 00:36:12.920
We got to get back in
the future business.

00:36:12.920 --> 00:36:16.610
That's certainly a big part of
what I talk about every day

00:36:16.610 --> 00:36:18.860
and try to connect some
dots in the book.

00:36:18.860 --> 00:36:21.330
And I do think there's
ways that we can

00:36:21.330 --> 00:36:23.520
substantially compete.

00:36:23.520 --> 00:36:25.430
And I'm not giving
up on our form of

00:36:25.430 --> 00:36:27.460
governance yet, though.

00:36:27.460 --> 00:36:29.570
MALE SPEAKER: Thanks for coming
to see us, Gavin.

00:36:29.570 --> 00:36:32.560
I think apathy is certainly
one of the huge issues our

00:36:32.560 --> 00:36:33.940
government's facing right now.

00:36:33.940 --> 00:36:35.930
But recently, the last couple
years since the Citizens

00:36:35.930 --> 00:36:38.950
United case, the super PAC
money, or as Colbert would

00:36:38.950 --> 00:36:41.680
call it, spooky PAC money,
seems to have--

00:36:41.680 --> 00:36:43.760
GAVIN NEWSOM: I contributed to
his Super PAC, by the way.

00:36:43.760 --> 00:36:44.150
MALE SPEAKER: Did you?

00:36:44.150 --> 00:36:44.450
Good job.

00:36:44.450 --> 00:36:44.720
So did I.

00:36:44.720 --> 00:36:44.980
GAVIN NEWSOM: I did.

00:36:44.980 --> 00:36:46.520
That's why I went on
his show, I think.

00:36:46.520 --> 00:36:47.470
I paid for that.

00:36:47.470 --> 00:36:49.810
MALE SPEAKER: You
paid for that.

00:36:49.810 --> 00:36:53.052
GAVIN NEWSOM: And did I
pay after I went on.

00:36:53.052 --> 00:36:54.770
I did "Meet the Press"
two days later.

00:36:54.770 --> 00:36:55.650
I was so relaxed.

00:36:55.650 --> 00:36:57.110
I'm like, oh, this is great.

00:36:57.110 --> 00:36:58.030
MALE SPEAKER: It was easy.

00:36:58.030 --> 00:36:58.820
GAVIN NEWSOM: Colbert, jeez.

00:36:58.820 --> 00:37:00.070
MALE SPEAKER: Everything's
easy [INAUDIBLE].

00:37:00.070 --> 00:37:00.920
GAVIN NEWSOM: I'll warn
Eric before he

00:37:00.920 --> 00:37:03.030
goes on his book tour.

00:37:03.030 --> 00:37:03.760
I'm just saying.

00:37:03.760 --> 00:37:06.330
Eric, if you're listening,
beware.

00:37:06.330 --> 00:37:08.840
MALE SPEAKER: So with that
threat still out there, do you

00:37:08.840 --> 00:37:12.370
see these new platforms, these
new ways of engagement, as

00:37:12.370 --> 00:37:15.670
ways to overcome what's going
on with Citizens United and

00:37:15.670 --> 00:37:16.250
Super PACs?

00:37:16.250 --> 00:37:19.000
Do we have to be worried about
movements being co-opted?

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:21.500
I think we saw a little bit with
the Tea Party movement

00:37:21.500 --> 00:37:24.480
and things like that of
groups coming in.

00:37:24.480 --> 00:37:26.770
How do we get around this?

00:37:26.770 --> 00:37:29.230
GAVIN NEWSOM: Maybe it's a bit
idealistic, but I think

00:37:29.230 --> 00:37:33.660
organized voices are more
powerful than organized money.

00:37:33.660 --> 00:37:37.000
I think the participatory nature
of social media, the

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:39.150
ability to engage,
self-organizing like

00:37:39.150 --> 00:37:42.890
[INAUDIBLE] communities,
ultimately will empower and

00:37:42.890 --> 00:37:46.900
engender a more successful
result than those that

00:37:46.900 --> 00:37:50.930
centralize and try to pick
winners and losers with a

00:37:50.930 --> 00:37:52.730
Super PAC framework
of engagement.

00:37:52.730 --> 00:37:57.430
It's interesting, of all people,
I got this strange--

00:37:57.430 --> 00:37:59.090
by definition, for me,
it was strange.

00:37:59.090 --> 00:38:01.040
It wasn't a strange email.

00:38:01.040 --> 00:38:06.140
But Newt Gingrich reached out
to me, called the book

00:38:06.140 --> 00:38:07.490
extraordinary.

00:38:07.490 --> 00:38:10.320
I responded in saying, I have
to re-read my book, Newt.

00:38:10.320 --> 00:38:12.090
I'll get back to you.

00:38:12.090 --> 00:38:14.380
MATTHEW: Did he tweet
about it?

00:38:14.380 --> 00:38:16.450
GAVIN NEWSOM: What the
hell was in this?

00:38:16.450 --> 00:38:20.980
And I kid you not, I sent him
another email late last night

00:38:20.980 --> 00:38:25.260
because he wrote a newsletter
reinforcing that, encouraging

00:38:25.260 --> 00:38:28.520
everyone to read this book
because he picked up on

00:38:28.520 --> 00:38:30.710
something that goes
to your question.

00:38:30.710 --> 00:38:34.480
He's in a big fight-- and he
didn't say this, but I now get

00:38:34.480 --> 00:38:37.850
it-- with Karl Rove because he
doesn't like what Rove's

00:38:37.850 --> 00:38:38.730
trying to do.

00:38:38.730 --> 00:38:41.940
And this is not about the
veracity of either argument,

00:38:41.940 --> 00:38:44.100
it's just an interesting
debate.

00:38:44.100 --> 00:38:46.200
Because Rove is trying to make
a case that we're going to

00:38:46.200 --> 00:38:50.100
pick and choose winners in these
states, so that they're

00:38:50.100 --> 00:38:54.460
more electable so we can take
back the Senate in 2014.

00:38:54.460 --> 00:38:57.550
And Gingrich is fiercely
fighting that because he

00:38:57.550 --> 00:39:01.410
believes that's a centralized
top-down frame where big money

00:39:01.410 --> 00:39:04.120
is trying to influence
elections.

00:39:04.120 --> 00:39:06.900
And his argument is bottom-up

00:39:06.900 --> 00:39:08.775
thinking, which is my argument.

00:39:08.775 --> 00:39:13.000
His argument is small-town
conservatism.

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:16.050
His argument is grass roots.

00:39:16.050 --> 00:39:17.610
And I find that interesting.

00:39:17.610 --> 00:39:20.590
And he was able to connect the
dots here on technology in

00:39:20.590 --> 00:39:25.090
looking at a 21st century form
of governing and organizing in

00:39:25.090 --> 00:39:27.950
relationship to what he would
call those Jeffersonian

00:39:27.950 --> 00:39:31.970
principles of individual liberty
and self-government.

00:39:31.970 --> 00:39:34.430
And so it goes back to your
question earlier, which is an

00:39:34.430 --> 00:39:38.110
interesting one, that there's
sort of an ideological

00:39:38.110 --> 00:39:40.880
bandwidth here that's a lot
broader than what you'd expect

00:39:40.880 --> 00:39:43.970
coming from an ex-mayor of San
Francisco and a Democratic

00:39:43.970 --> 00:39:45.290
lieutenant governor from
one of the bluest

00:39:45.290 --> 00:39:47.030
states in our nation.

00:39:47.030 --> 00:39:48.880
MATTHEW: It goes to what you
said about change.gov as well,

00:39:48.880 --> 00:39:50.820
which is it's very difficult
to get these

00:39:50.820 --> 00:39:51.990
tools right, initially.

00:39:51.990 --> 00:39:55.660
I think we collectively had
some first missteps that I

00:39:55.660 --> 00:39:56.360
think we'll learn from.

00:39:56.360 --> 00:39:57.750
But the tools have
to be smarter.

00:39:57.750 --> 00:40:01.370
And they have to weed out, I
guess, the spammers and people

00:40:01.370 --> 00:40:04.040
who are misguiding it or
try and co-opt it.

00:40:04.040 --> 00:40:05.190
And we have a lot of experience
with this as

00:40:05.190 --> 00:40:07.590
company I think with communities
that we have to

00:40:07.590 --> 00:40:10.250
curate and work with YouTube
and so forth.

00:40:10.250 --> 00:40:13.020
I think a lot of that will have
to work in the political

00:40:13.020 --> 00:40:13.730
sphere, too.

00:40:13.730 --> 00:40:15.220
Otherwise, it could
be co-opted.

00:40:15.220 --> 00:40:16.165
GAVIN NEWSOM: Yeah,
that's true.

00:40:16.165 --> 00:40:18.850
MALE SPEAKER: I don't know if
you are familiar in the last

00:40:18.850 --> 00:40:23.800
elections in November, there
was a young 18-year-old who

00:40:23.800 --> 00:40:27.300
ran for mayor of Fremont.

00:40:27.300 --> 00:40:28.830
He's my son, by the way.

00:40:28.830 --> 00:40:31.830
[APPLAUSE]

00:40:31.830 --> 00:40:34.680
MALE SPEAKER: And he ran on the
platform of something just

00:40:34.680 --> 00:40:36.890
along the lines of what
you're talking about.

00:40:36.890 --> 00:40:39.670
He wanted to bring about
transformational change in the

00:40:39.670 --> 00:40:40.560
government.

00:40:40.560 --> 00:40:44.150
And how the government should
start thinking out of the box

00:40:44.150 --> 00:40:48.160
and bring about innovative
solutions in how to govern.

00:40:48.160 --> 00:40:50.510
And obviously, he didn't win.

00:40:50.510 --> 00:40:54.540
But he still has a passion
and he has the energy.

00:40:54.540 --> 00:40:59.490
What advice would you have for
young people like him to join

00:40:59.490 --> 00:41:02.370
politics, and how do they
bring about change?

00:41:02.370 --> 00:41:02.930
GAVIN NEWSOM: I love it.

00:41:02.930 --> 00:41:03.683
Thank you, and congrats.

00:41:03.683 --> 00:41:05.540
And you're obviously a good role
model that you encouraged

00:41:05.540 --> 00:41:08.510
him to do it at a
remarkable age.

00:41:08.510 --> 00:41:10.110
Two thoughts on this.

00:41:10.110 --> 00:41:12.050
First thing is you're absolutely
right, I'm arguing

00:41:12.050 --> 00:41:13.860
for a different division
of labor.

00:41:13.860 --> 00:41:16.210
I'm not arguing for
e-government.

00:41:16.210 --> 00:41:19.540
That's happening
on the natural.

00:41:19.540 --> 00:41:21.790
And I hate this phrase, but
I'll use it because it

00:41:21.790 --> 00:41:26.070
simplifies it, I'm arguing
for we government.

00:41:26.070 --> 00:41:29.790
I want more voices
and more choices.

00:41:29.790 --> 00:41:33.940
I want to devolve and
involve people into

00:41:33.940 --> 00:41:35.920
building sense of community.

00:41:35.920 --> 00:41:38.940
I support real participatory
budgeting along the lines of

00:41:38.940 --> 00:41:40.480
what Brazil's been doing.

00:41:40.480 --> 00:41:43.550
New York just started a
small version of this.

00:41:43.550 --> 00:41:46.570
Real, active citizen engagement,
not inert

00:41:46.570 --> 00:41:47.180
citizenship.

00:41:47.180 --> 00:41:48.670
So that's the argument.

00:41:48.670 --> 00:41:51.580
But I also make an argument
in this book--

00:41:51.580 --> 00:41:56.510
and this is my advice to your
son, that this is a book about

00:41:56.510 --> 00:41:57.740
leadership.

00:41:57.740 --> 00:41:59.570
And I make the case that--

00:41:59.570 --> 00:42:00.430
and this is my belief.

00:42:00.430 --> 00:42:01.910
Good people can disagree.

00:42:01.910 --> 00:42:06.130
That we've got it wrong holding
it out for this guy or

00:42:06.130 --> 00:42:08.820
gal on the white horse to come
in and save our day.

00:42:08.820 --> 00:42:11.010
I don't buy that anymore.

00:42:11.010 --> 00:42:14.150
My father years and years ago
used to make this point and it

00:42:14.150 --> 00:42:17.370
came together when Tom Peters
wrote about this years ago,

00:42:17.370 --> 00:42:19.130
and he really distilled it.

00:42:19.130 --> 00:42:28.920
What did Dr. King, Gandhi,
Mandela, and Havel all have in

00:42:28.920 --> 00:42:30.570
common at the peak of
their influence?

00:42:30.570 --> 00:42:34.940
Havel, King, Mandela, Gandhi,
the peak of their influence,

00:42:34.940 --> 00:42:37.100
what did they have in common?

00:42:37.100 --> 00:42:39.170
Jail time.

00:42:39.170 --> 00:42:40.800
Interesting fact.

00:42:40.800 --> 00:42:42.280
But they also had something
else in common.

00:42:42.280 --> 00:42:45.500
They exercised their
moral authority.

00:42:45.500 --> 00:42:46.700
None of them had formal
authority.

00:42:46.700 --> 00:42:49.910
In fact, you could argue that
when Vaclav Havel--

00:42:49.910 --> 00:42:52.740
in fact, he argued himself in
a lot of his writings--

00:42:52.740 --> 00:42:55.100
became president of
Czechoslovakia, he lost a lot

00:42:55.100 --> 00:42:56.650
of his influence.

00:42:56.650 --> 00:43:00.730
Same with Mandela after getting
formal authority in

00:43:00.730 --> 00:43:01.830
South Africa.

00:43:01.830 --> 00:43:06.110
And so my advice to your son
is to consider that.

00:43:06.110 --> 00:43:06.910
You don't need to be--

00:43:06.910 --> 00:43:07.760
MATTHEW: Go to prison?

00:43:07.760 --> 00:43:08.515
GAVIN NEWSOM: No.

00:43:08.515 --> 00:43:10.990
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:10.990 --> 00:43:12.760
MATTHEW: OK, just being clear.

00:43:12.760 --> 00:43:15.650
GAVIN NEWSOM: The moral
component of that.

00:43:15.650 --> 00:43:17.605
But if he must, he must.

00:43:17.605 --> 00:43:19.950
We sure as heck risked it
as you said when we

00:43:19.950 --> 00:43:22.200
broke the law in 2004.

00:43:22.200 --> 00:43:23.680
I thought I'd be recalled
and arrested.

00:43:23.680 --> 00:43:24.540
I really did.

00:43:24.540 --> 00:43:27.300
Was willing to do that to put
a human face on an issue of

00:43:27.300 --> 00:43:29.040
something I cared about because
I didn't want to wait

00:43:29.040 --> 00:43:33.020
30 years, as was the case with
interracial marriage, to one

00:43:33.020 --> 00:43:35.190
day see it happen
in my lifetime.

00:43:35.190 --> 00:43:37.150
Here we are nine years later
and we may see it in a few

00:43:37.150 --> 00:43:39.510
weeks at the Supreme Court.

00:43:39.510 --> 00:43:43.730
That said, to consider that you
don't need to be something

00:43:43.730 --> 00:43:45.000
to do something.

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:47.950
You don't need to be somebody
to do something.

00:43:47.950 --> 00:43:49.970
Exercise your moral authority.

00:43:49.970 --> 00:43:52.580
And make the determination of
whether or not being part of

00:43:52.580 --> 00:43:56.690
the system is actually better
than being outside the system.

00:43:56.690 --> 00:43:58.640
Maybe it's good he
lost is my point.

00:43:58.640 --> 00:44:00.730
Final point, back
to the we always

00:44:00.730 --> 00:44:02.200
are now quoting Lincoln.

00:44:02.200 --> 00:44:04.790
The one quote I never hear of
Lincoln that I love says we're

00:44:04.790 --> 00:44:09.740
all born originals but
we die copies.

00:44:09.740 --> 00:44:12.540
And I think of that in the
context particularly of

00:44:12.540 --> 00:44:14.950
politicians and elections.

00:44:14.950 --> 00:44:16.660
We watch those campaign
commercials and you're like,

00:44:16.660 --> 00:44:19.380
wow, that guy or gal,
she's great.

00:44:19.380 --> 00:44:20.610
So creative.

00:44:20.610 --> 00:44:21.570
So passionate.

00:44:21.570 --> 00:44:22.970
So authentic.

00:44:22.970 --> 00:44:27.110
And then you look back 15
years later when they're

00:44:27.110 --> 00:44:30.130
termed out and you say,
man, they just--

00:44:30.130 --> 00:44:31.660
what happened to that person?

00:44:31.660 --> 00:44:33.100
They're like everybody else.

00:44:33.100 --> 00:44:37.820
It's as if the process of
governing de-geniuses you.

00:44:37.820 --> 00:44:40.700
The system de-geniuses you.

00:44:40.700 --> 00:44:44.000
Originality is lost because of
the way things are done.

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:46.500
Remember, Obama again, let's
not-- he was right and he

00:44:46.500 --> 00:44:47.480
struggled with this.

00:44:47.480 --> 00:44:48.880
We don't want to change
the players, we want

00:44:48.880 --> 00:44:50.135
to change the game.

00:44:50.135 --> 00:44:52.220
And that's my argument
in this book.

00:44:52.220 --> 00:44:55.910
We've got to redesign, as your
son wanted to redesign, that

00:44:55.910 --> 00:44:56.860
engagement.

00:44:56.860 --> 00:45:00.810
And redesign our thinking and
consciousness around the role

00:45:00.810 --> 00:45:04.110
of government and the role of
citizens in relationship to

00:45:04.110 --> 00:45:05.360
our governing institution.

00:45:07.770 --> 00:45:08.460
MALE SPEAKER: Hi, Gavin.

00:45:08.460 --> 00:45:12.800
I'm wondering how we can
institute a gamification of

00:45:12.800 --> 00:45:16.620
the political while still
keeping the rhetoric relevant.

00:45:16.620 --> 00:45:18.850
So for every White House
petition for unlocking

00:45:18.850 --> 00:45:21.760
cellphones, we have one about
the Death Star and we have one

00:45:21.760 --> 00:45:22.570
about R. Kelly's [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:22.570 --> 00:45:24.110
GAVIN NEWSOM: You don't feel
the Death Star's important?

00:45:24.110 --> 00:45:25.420
MALE SPEAKER: I do, but--

00:45:25.420 --> 00:45:29.680
GAVIN NEWSOM: What about
deporting Piers Morgan?

00:45:29.680 --> 00:45:30.930
How about daylight
savings latest

00:45:30.930 --> 00:45:34.840
petition coming this Sunday?

00:45:34.840 --> 00:45:36.090
Good point.

00:45:38.110 --> 00:45:40.160
Tim O'Reilly-- we had a great
conversation in this book

00:45:40.160 --> 00:45:40.990
about this.

00:45:40.990 --> 00:45:43.490
And he made this case, and the
reason I put it in is I agree

00:45:43.490 --> 00:45:46.590
with him 100%, that this is
not about creating a new

00:45:46.590 --> 00:45:48.190
framework of petitioning
government to

00:45:48.190 --> 00:45:50.150
do things for you.

00:45:50.150 --> 00:45:54.340
This is about creating new
mechanisms to do things with

00:45:54.340 --> 00:45:56.260
government.

00:45:56.260 --> 00:45:59.680
This is about creating a new
platform and framework of real

00:45:59.680 --> 00:46:01.260
engagement.

00:46:01.260 --> 00:46:05.300
President Obama, as you know,
took the change.gov and now

00:46:05.300 --> 00:46:07.790
it's done something called
We the People.

00:46:07.790 --> 00:46:12.190
And after 5,000 virtual
petitions, Jay Carney at the

00:46:12.190 --> 00:46:15.360
White House would respond to
any of those petitions.

00:46:15.360 --> 00:46:18.050
And the Death Star was one of
the dominant petitions.

00:46:18.050 --> 00:46:19.100
They kind of disregarded that.

00:46:19.100 --> 00:46:20.440
The press disregard that.

00:46:20.440 --> 00:46:22.330
But the Piers Morgan example
was infamous.

00:46:22.330 --> 00:46:25.830
Because right after the NRA went
after Piers, there was a

00:46:25.830 --> 00:46:29.710
big petition to deport Piers
back to the country that

00:46:29.710 --> 00:46:32.890
forced us to bear arms
in the first place--

00:46:32.890 --> 00:46:34.440
those Brits.

00:46:34.440 --> 00:46:36.442
And it got 70-plus-thousand.

00:46:36.442 --> 00:46:39.260
And there's Carney in the
beginning of the debate around

00:46:39.260 --> 00:46:41.430
drones going you've
got to be kidding.

00:46:41.430 --> 00:46:44.580
Guy is on CNN and I have
to respond to this?

00:46:44.580 --> 00:46:46.560
So what did the White
House decide to do?

00:46:46.560 --> 00:46:49.550
They decided to raise the
threshold for petitions before

00:46:49.550 --> 00:46:51.840
they respond, missing
the whole point.

00:46:51.840 --> 00:46:55.060
It's not about petitioning
folks with the machine

00:46:55.060 --> 00:46:57.540
thinking to do things for you.

00:46:57.540 --> 00:47:00.340
It's about that again, new
division of labor and

00:47:00.340 --> 00:47:02.070
different kind of engagement.

00:47:02.070 --> 00:47:04.630
MALE SPEAKER: This is sort of
an ideological question, but

00:47:04.630 --> 00:47:07.440
you touched upon this earlier.

00:47:07.440 --> 00:47:12.900
Why is the public sector so
inefficient and so averse to

00:47:12.900 --> 00:47:15.040
change compared to the
private sector?

00:47:15.040 --> 00:47:16.490
GAVIN NEWSOM: Well, it's the
old adage, move the mouse,

00:47:16.490 --> 00:47:17.310
move the cheese.

00:47:17.310 --> 00:47:20.430
You want to move it, you
got to move the cheese.

00:47:20.430 --> 00:47:23.190
There's no incentive
for good behavior.

00:47:23.190 --> 00:47:25.350
There's incentive for
terrible behavior.

00:47:25.350 --> 00:47:27.390
Every single person's
acting in their best

00:47:27.390 --> 00:47:28.920
interest all of the time.

00:47:28.920 --> 00:47:31.170
It's a remarkably efficient
thing and it's rather

00:47:31.170 --> 00:47:32.360
predictable.

00:47:32.360 --> 00:47:34.270
The sequestration is a perfect
example of that.

00:47:34.270 --> 00:47:36.750
It's in everyone's interest
to do what they've done.

00:47:36.750 --> 00:47:39.320
Otherwise, they wouldn't
do it.

00:47:39.320 --> 00:47:41.250
I mean, you think about
Congress in

00:47:41.250 --> 00:47:42.650
single digit ratings.

00:47:42.650 --> 00:47:45.350
I mean literally, you remember
the debater around NFL

00:47:45.350 --> 00:47:46.510
replacement refs?

00:47:46.510 --> 00:47:49.550
There was a new poll just came
out that shows three to one

00:47:49.550 --> 00:47:54.702
people prefer the NFL
replacement refs to Congress,

00:47:54.702 --> 00:47:58.760
which I just think
sums it all up.

00:47:58.760 --> 00:48:03.450
But yet, Republican Congress
in single digits won

00:48:03.450 --> 00:48:05.630
reelection rather
overwhelmingly.

00:48:05.630 --> 00:48:06.720
They only lost eight seats.

00:48:06.720 --> 00:48:08.025
I mean, they may seem
significant.

00:48:08.025 --> 00:48:09.190
But at the end of the
day, they held

00:48:09.190 --> 00:48:10.710
onto a strong majority.

00:48:10.710 --> 00:48:13.390
Just two seats in the Senate.

00:48:13.390 --> 00:48:17.160
We act in our best interest
because the system's designed

00:48:17.160 --> 00:48:18.710
for inefficiency.

00:48:18.710 --> 00:48:20.700
We are a monopoly.

00:48:20.700 --> 00:48:25.220
The only way you get fired is
actually working outside of

00:48:25.220 --> 00:48:28.110
your job description.

00:48:28.110 --> 00:48:31.130
The reason I have a failure
award in my businesses, why I

00:48:31.130 --> 00:48:36.720
reward the biggest screwup, is
I can't stand the contrast

00:48:36.720 --> 00:48:41.035
with my day job as lieutenant
governor in government.

00:48:41.035 --> 00:48:42.560
I have a little hotel,
just very, very

00:48:42.560 --> 00:48:43.910
briefly up in Tahoe.

00:48:43.910 --> 00:48:45.346
A lot of mosquitoes
during the winter.

00:48:45.346 --> 00:48:48.550
It was built in 1959 for the
delegates of the Olympics, the

00:48:48.550 --> 00:48:49.390
'60 Olympics.

00:48:49.390 --> 00:48:50.160
So it's an old hotel.

00:48:50.160 --> 00:48:51.240
We don't have air
conditioning.

00:48:51.240 --> 00:48:54.520
So we keep the doors to the
hallways open in the summer.

00:48:54.520 --> 00:48:56.220
I had one of those
eccentric folks.

00:48:56.220 --> 00:48:58.290
They're all eccentric,
those night clerks.

00:48:58.290 --> 00:48:59.790
The guy when you check in at
2:00 in the morning you go,

00:48:59.790 --> 00:49:00.550
who is this person?

00:49:00.550 --> 00:49:02.480
Why would you have this job?

00:49:02.480 --> 00:49:05.420
And this guy decided on his own
before he came to work at

00:49:05.420 --> 00:49:10.770
11 o'clock at night to buy a
bunch of catfish because he

00:49:10.770 --> 00:49:12.220
thought-- it was an
interesting idea.

00:49:12.220 --> 00:49:13.700
He said, I'm going to take the
catfish and put it in all the

00:49:13.700 --> 00:49:17.960
ponds outside of the hotel so
they after the mosquitoes.

00:49:17.960 --> 00:49:21.010
Maybe we'll reduce the problem
we have with mosquitoes.

00:49:21.010 --> 00:49:23.570
Well, he leaves about 5:00 in
the morning and Ludo, who had

00:49:23.570 --> 00:49:24.220
been with me for--

00:49:24.220 --> 00:49:26.600
I don't know, 14, 15 years--
my engineer,

00:49:26.600 --> 00:49:28.600
never once called me.

00:49:28.600 --> 00:49:30.360
Wakes me up.

00:49:30.360 --> 00:49:31.590
Goes, I can't believe this.

00:49:31.590 --> 00:49:34.380
I don't know what to say, but
you have to hear this.

00:49:34.380 --> 00:49:35.200
It's the strangest thing.

00:49:35.200 --> 00:49:36.520
I think we've been vandalized.

00:49:36.520 --> 00:49:38.650
But all throughout the hotel--

00:49:38.650 --> 00:49:40.060
and It.

00:49:40.060 --> 00:49:40.650
Could be worse.

00:49:40.650 --> 00:49:41.320
This is strange.

00:49:41.320 --> 00:49:43.340
But there's eyeballs of fish.

00:49:43.340 --> 00:49:44.760
There's tails.

00:49:44.760 --> 00:49:45.990
There's all these fish.

00:49:45.990 --> 00:49:47.540
I mean, it's just chaotic.

00:49:47.540 --> 00:49:48.820
Bones.

00:49:48.820 --> 00:49:50.350
So I'm going call
you right back.

00:49:50.350 --> 00:49:51.720
I just need to let
you know this.

00:49:51.720 --> 00:49:53.030
I'm like, what the
hell is this?

00:49:53.030 --> 00:49:55.220
I said, figure this thing out.

00:49:55.220 --> 00:49:58.430
Calls me back a couple hours
later and figured it out.

00:49:58.430 --> 00:50:00.720
Our night clerk went out,
bought catfish,

00:50:00.720 --> 00:50:01.870
put them in the ponds.

00:50:01.870 --> 00:50:02.980
And what happened?

00:50:02.980 --> 00:50:10.090
The raccoons got in in total
delirium, wildly enthusiastic,

00:50:10.090 --> 00:50:14.040
running around, were running
through the hotel, and

00:50:14.040 --> 00:50:17.460
throwing the carcasses all
around, et cetera.

00:50:17.460 --> 00:50:22.750
And so I heard this relieved and
was inspired to create the

00:50:22.750 --> 00:50:23.460
failure award.

00:50:23.460 --> 00:50:26.650
I gave this guy an $800
bonus because it was

00:50:26.650 --> 00:50:28.700
such a glorious failure.

00:50:28.700 --> 00:50:32.860
And it contrasted so well to my
days in San Francisco as a

00:50:32.860 --> 00:50:36.750
supervisor at the time where
the only-- if something

00:50:36.750 --> 00:50:39.920
happened like that, that person
would have been fired.

00:50:39.920 --> 00:50:44.340
As opposed to celebrating a
glorious failure and learning

00:50:44.340 --> 00:50:47.410
from it because the guy
had initiative.

00:50:47.410 --> 00:50:49.270
And I'll close with this,
just to underscore.

00:50:49.270 --> 00:50:50.520
I'm a big labor guy.

00:50:50.520 --> 00:50:53.450
We're a $10.55 minimum
wage city.

00:50:53.450 --> 00:50:55.280
We have universal preschool,
not just

00:50:55.280 --> 00:50:56.480
universal health care.

00:50:56.480 --> 00:50:58.080
Heck, our kindergarten
students.

00:50:58.080 --> 00:51:01.190
I created sometime I'm so proud
of called K through 12

00:51:01.190 --> 00:51:04.240
where we're giving little
college savings accounts to

00:51:04.240 --> 00:51:07.230
every single person that enters
into kindergarten gets

00:51:07.230 --> 00:51:09.295
their own online bank account.

00:51:09.295 --> 00:51:12.230
It starts small, but it
creates a mindset of

00:51:12.230 --> 00:51:12.525
expectation.

00:51:12.525 --> 00:51:15.040
The old adage, once a mind's
stretched, it never goes back

00:51:15.040 --> 00:51:15.820
to its original form.

00:51:15.820 --> 00:51:18.280
We're a pretty progressive
place.

00:51:18.280 --> 00:51:20.640
And labor's been sponsored,
all those things.

00:51:20.640 --> 00:51:21.300
They've been fabulous.

00:51:21.300 --> 00:51:24.520
But there was a big contract
that said performance reviews

00:51:24.520 --> 00:51:27.390
and disciplinary records cannot
be considered with

00:51:27.390 --> 00:51:28.085
regard to promotion.

00:51:28.085 --> 00:51:29.470
I'll repeat that.

00:51:29.470 --> 00:51:32.640
The largest public employee in
San Francisco said performance

00:51:32.640 --> 00:51:36.280
reviews comma disciplinary
records cannot be considered

00:51:36.280 --> 00:51:37.170
with regard to promotion.

00:51:37.170 --> 00:51:38.460
Imagine if Google had that?

00:51:42.400 --> 00:51:43.650
Hey, that'd be great.

00:51:43.650 --> 00:51:45.550
You want to go to Tahoe today?

00:51:48.090 --> 00:51:49.980
And I just thought it was
a demoralizing thing.

00:51:49.980 --> 00:51:51.990
And I fought to take that out.

00:51:51.990 --> 00:51:56.530
And the point was we only
celebrated the success of

00:51:56.530 --> 00:51:59.060
someone just being around an
extra few days or months or

00:51:59.060 --> 00:52:02.220
years, but not someone's
creativity,

00:52:02.220 --> 00:52:04.080
not someone's genius.

00:52:04.080 --> 00:52:06.990
And that's the kind of incentive
that's going to

00:52:06.990 --> 00:52:11.870
elevate our quality and our
capacity to improve.

00:52:11.870 --> 00:52:15.800
And that created that friction,
that stress that

00:52:15.800 --> 00:52:18.600
I've had over these years
living in both worlds.

00:52:18.600 --> 00:52:20.370
And frankly, what I hope--

00:52:20.370 --> 00:52:23.460
long-winded way of wrapping
things up--

00:52:23.460 --> 00:52:27.430
that in this book I provide
some specific tangible

00:52:27.430 --> 00:52:31.500
examples to begin to address a
hybrid of these two principles

00:52:31.500 --> 00:52:36.330
and philosophy so that, in
closing, government can become

00:52:36.330 --> 00:52:39.350
as smart as Google.

00:52:39.350 --> 00:52:40.550
Thank you, guys.

00:52:40.550 --> 00:52:41.450
MATTHEW: Thank you very much.

00:52:41.450 --> 00:52:42.050
GAVIN NEWSOM: Thanks.

00:52:42.050 --> 00:52:47.150
[APPLAUSE]

00:52:47.150 --> 00:53:13.625
